## Important note on work in progress

The wetland ecosystem protection level analysis is built on a robust interim wetland ecosystem typology. However, the refinement of the national wetland ecosystem typology was still underway at the time of this assessment. This ongoing process to refine the interim typology into more detailed, validated subtypes is being undertaken in collaboration with multiple research partners. It will soon result in minor adjustments and an updated assessment, which will be widely communicated.

::: {#box-1 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 1. Primary Catchments and Inland Wetland Ecosystem Protection Level" collapse="true"}
South Africa supports 22 primary catchments which are further grouped into six Water Management Areas. These are the Vaal-Orange, Pongola-Umzimkhulu, Mzimvubu-Tsitsikamma, Limpopo-Olifants, Breede-Olifants, and Inkomati-Usuthu. Each WMA is managed by an established or in process Catchment Management Agency responsible for overseeing the allocation, protection, and conservation of water resources in the catchment.

To support the consideration of biodiversity into emerging Catchment Management Strategies and implementation plans, the inland wetland ecosystem threat status headline indicator is presented according to the 22 primary catchments and associated Water Management Area.

Table 1.1. Ecosystem Protection Level of inland wetlands according to primary catchment and Water Management Area.
:::

::: {#box-2 .callout-note .freshwater title="Box 2. Inland Wetland Ecosystem Protection Level across the Provinces" collapse="true"}
The national status of inland wetland ecosystems is summarised according to each of the nine provinces and can serve as foundational information to support provinces as they prepare their state of environment reports and other freshwater biodiversity planning initiatives.

Table 2.1. Ecosystem Protection Level of inland wetlands across the provinces of South Africa.

In the face of prevailing financial and capacity constraints to implementing large-scale inventory across the country, there is a focus on expanding the mapping and validation of extent, ecological condition and characteristics of wetlands within Provincial Nature Reserves, ultimately contributing to the continuous refinement of the national wetland map. The current data reflects ongoing collaborative efforts between national and provincial agencies.
